[src:web-serial/api-serial] This feature is not Baseline because it does not work in some of the most widely-used browsers.
[src:web-serial/api-serial] The `Serial` interface of the Web Serial API provides attributes and methods for finding and connecting to serial ports from a web page.
[src:web-serial/api-serial] Returns a `Promise` that resolves with an instance of `SerialPort` representing the device chosen by the user.
[src:web-serial/api-serial] This method must be called via transient activation.
[src:web-serial/api-serial] Returns a `Promise` that resolves with an array of `SerialPort` objects representing serial ports connected to the host that the origin has permission to access.
[src:web-serial/api-serial] An event fired when a port has been connected to the device.
[src:web-serial/api-serial] An event fired when a port has been disconnected from the device.
[src:web-serial/api-serial] The following example shows how a site can check for available ports and allow the user to grant it permission to access additional ports.
[src:web-serial/api-serial] On load event listeners are added for the `connect` and `disconnect` events so that the site can react when a device is connected or disconnected from the system.
[src:web-serial/api-serial] The `getPorts()` method is then called to see which ports are connected that the site already has access to.
[src:web-serial/api-serial] If the site doesn't have access to any connected ports it has to wait until it has user activation to proceed.
[src:web-serial/api-serial] In this example we use a `click` event handler on a button for this task.
[src:web-serial/api-serial] A filter is passed to `requestPort()` with a USB vendor ID in order to limit the set of devices shown to the user to only USB devices built by a particular manufacturer.
[src:web-serial/api-serialport] The `SerialPort` interface of the Web Serial API provides access to a serial port on the host device.
[src:web-serial/api-serialport] Instances of this interface may be obtained by calling methods of the `Serial` interface, therefore it has no constructor of its own.
[src:web-serial/api-serialport] Returns a boolean value that indicates whether the port is logically connected to the device.
[src:web-serial/api-serialport] Returns a `ReadableStream` for receiving data from the device connected to the port.
[src:web-serial/api-serialport] Returns a `WritableStream` for sending data to the device connected to the port.
[src:web-serial/api-serialport] Returns a `Promise` that resolves when access to the serial port is revoked.
[src:web-serial/api-serialport] Calling this "forgets" the device, resetting any previously-set permissions so the calling site can no longer communicate with the port.
[src:web-serial/api-serialport] Returns an object containing identifying information for the device available via the port.
[src:web-serial/api-serialport] Returns a `Promise` that resolves when the port is opened.
[src:web-serial/api-serialport] By default the port is opened with 8 data bits, 1 stop bit and no parity checking.
[src:web-serial/api-serialport] Sets control signals on the port and returns a `Promise` that resolves when they are set.
[src:web-serial/api-serialport] Returns a `Promise` that resolves with an object containing the current state of the port's control signals.
[src:web-serial/api-serialport] Returns a `Promise` that resolves when the port closes.
[src:web-serial/api-serialport] Fired when the port connects to the device.
[src:web-serial/api-serialport] Fired when the port disconnects from the device.
[src:web-serial/api-serialport] Before communicating on a serial port it must be opened.
[src:web-serial/api-serialport] Opening the port allows the site to specify the necessary parameters that control how data is transmitted and received.
[src:web-serial/api-serialport] Developers should check the documentation for the device they are connecting to for the appropriate parameters.
[src:web-serial/api-serialport] Once the `Promise` returned by `open()` resolves the `readable` and `writable` attributes can be accessed to get the `ReadableStream` and `WritableStream` instances for receiving data from and sending data to the connected device.
