[src:web-serial/serial-communication] In telecommunication and data transmission, **serial communication** is the process of sending data one bit at a time, sequentially, over a communication channel or computer bus.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] This is in contrast to parallel communication, where several bits are sent as a whole, on a link with several parallel channels.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] Serial communication is used for all long-haul communication and most computer networks, where the cost of cable and difficulty of synchronization make parallel communication impractical.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] The migration from PCI to PCI Express (PCIe) is an example.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] Modern high speed serial interfaces such as PCIe send data several bits at a time using modulation/encoding techniques such as PAM4 which groups 2 bits at a time into a single symbol, and several symbols are still sent one at a time.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] This replaces PAM2 or non return to zero (NRZ) which only sends one bit at a time, or in other words one bit per symbol.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] The symbols are sent at a speed known as the symbol rate or the baud rate.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] Many serial communication systems were originally designed to transfer data over relatively large distances through some sort of data cable.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] Practically all long-distance communication transmits data one bit at a time, rather than in parallel, because it reduces the cost of the cable.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] The cables that carry this data (other than "the" serial cable) and the computer ports they plug into are usually referred to with a more specific name, to reduce confusion.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] Keyboard and mouse cables and ports are almost invariably serial—such as PS/2 port, Apple Desktop Bus and USB.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] The cables that carry digital video are also mostly serial—such as coax cable plugged into a HD-SDI port, a webcam plugged into a USB port or FireWire port, Ethernet cable connecting an IP camera to a Power over Ethernet port, FPD-Link, digital telephone lines (ex.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] Other such cables and ports, transmitting data one bit at a time, include Serial ATA, Serial SCSI, Ethernet cable plugged into Ethernet ports, the Display Data Channel using previously reserved pins of the VGA connector or the DVI port or the HDMI port.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] Many communication systems were generally designed to connect two integrated circuits on the same printed circuit board, connected by signal traces on that board (rather than external cables).
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] Integrated circuits are more expensive when they have more pins.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] To reduce the number of pins in a package, many ICs use a serial bus to transfer data when speed is not important.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] Some examples of such low-cost lower-speed serial buses include RS-232, DALI, SPI, CAN bus, I²C, UNI/O, and 1-Wire.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] Higher-speed serial buses include USB, SATA and PCI Express.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] The communication links, across which computers (or parts of computers) talk to one another, may be either serial or parallel.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] A parallel link transmits several streams of data simultaneously along multiple channels (e.g., wires, printed circuit tracks, or optical fibers); whereas, a serial link transmits only a single stream of data.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] The rationale for parallel communication was the added benefit of having Direct Memory Access to the 8-bit or 16-bit registry addresses at a time when mapping direct data lanes was more convenient and faster than synchronizing data serially.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] Although a serial link may seem inferior to a parallel one, since it can transmit less data per clock cycle, it is often the case that serial links can be clocked considerably faster than parallel links in order to achieve a higher data rate.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] The transition from parallel to serial buses was allowed by Moore's law which allowed for the incorporation of SerDes in integrated circuits.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] An electrical serial link only requires a pair of wires, whereas a parallel link requires several.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] Thus serial links can save on costs (also known as the Bill of Materials).
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] Differential signalling uses length-matched wires or conductors and are used in high speed serial links.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] Length-matching is easier to perform on serial links as they require fewer conductors.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] In many cases, serial is cheaper to implement than parallel.
[src:web-serial/serial-communication] Many ICs have serial interfaces, as opposed to parallel ones, so that they have fewer pins and are therefore less expensive.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] A **serial port** is a serial communication interface through which information transfers in or out sequentially one bit at a time.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] This is in contrast to a parallel port, which communicates multiple bits simultaneously in parallel.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Throughout most of the history of personal computers, data has been transferred through serial ports to devices such as modems, terminals, various peripherals, and directly between computers.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] While interfaces such as Ethernet, FireWire, and USB also send data as a serial stream, the term *serial port* usually denotes hardware compliant with RS-232 or a related standard, such as RS-485 or RS-422.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Modern consumer personal computers (PCs) have largely replaced serial ports with higher-speed standards, primarily USB.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] However, serial ports are still frequently used in applications demanding simple, low-speed interfaces, such as industrial automation systems, scientific instruments, point of sale systems and some industrial and consumer products.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Server computers may use a serial port as a control console for diagnostics, while networking hardware (such as routers and switches) commonly use serial console ports for configuration, diagnostics, and emergency maintenance access.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] To interface with these and other devices, USB-to-serial adapters can quickly and easily add a serial port to a modern PC.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Modern devices use an integrated circuit called a UART to implement a serial port.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] This IC converts characters to and from asynchronous serial form, implementing the timing and framing of data specified by the serial protocol in hardware.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The IBM PC implements its serial ports, when present, with one or more UARTs.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Very low-cost systems, such as some early home computers, would instead use the CPU to send the data through an output pin, using the bit banging technique.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] These early home computers often had proprietary serial ports with pinouts and voltage levels incompatible with RS-232.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Before large-scale integration (LSI) made UARTs common, serial ports were commonly used in mainframes and minicomputers, which would have multiple small-scale integrated circuits to implement shift registers, logic gates, counters, and all the other logic needed.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] As PCs evolved, serial ports were included in the Super I/O chip and then in the chipset.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The individual signals on a serial port are unidirectional and when connecting two devices, the outputs of one device must be connected to the inputs of the other.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Devices are divided into two categories: *data terminal equipment* (DTE) and *data circuit-terminating equipment* (DCE).
[src:web-serial/serial-port] A line that is an output on a DTE device is an input on a DCE device and vice versa, so a DCE device can be connected to a DTE device with a straight-wired cable, in which each pin on one end goes to the same numbered pin on the other end.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Conventionally, computers and terminals are DTE, while peripherals such as modems are DCE.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] If it is necessary to connect two DTE (or DCE) devices together, a cable with reversed TX and RX lines, known as a cross-over, roll-over or null modem cable must be used.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Generally, serial port connectors are gendered, only allowing connectors to mate with a connector of the opposite gender.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] With D-subminiature connectors, the male connectors have protruding pins and female connectors have corresponding round sockets.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Either type of connector can be mounted on equipment or a panel; or terminate a cable.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Connectors mounted on DTE are likely to be male, and those mounted on DCE are likely to be female (with the cable connectors being the opposite).
[src:web-serial/serial-port] However, this is far from universal; for instance, most serial printers have a female DB25 connector, but they are DTEs.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] In this circumstance, the appropriately gendered connectors on the cable or a gender changer can be used to correct the mismatch.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The only connector specified in the original RS-232 standard was the 25-pin D-subminiature; however, many other connectors have been used to save money or save on physical space, among other reasons.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] In particular, since many devices do not use all of the 20 signals that are defined by the standard, connectors with fewer pins are often used.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] While specific examples follow, countless other connectors have been used for RS-232 connections.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The 9-pin DE-9 connector has been used by most IBM-compatible PCs since the Serial/Parallel Adapter option for the PC-AT, where the 9-pin connector allowed a serial and parallel port to fit on the same card.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] This connector has been standardized for RS-232 as TIA-574.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Some miniaturized electronics, particularly graphing calculators and hand-held amateur and two-way radio equipment, have serial ports using a phone connector, usually the smaller 2.5 or 3.5 mm connectors and the most basic 3-wire interface—transmit, receive and ground.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] 8P8C connectors are also used in many devices.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The EIA/TIA-561 standard defines a pinout using this connector, while the rollover cable (or Yost standard) is commonly used on Unix computers and network devices, such as equipment from Cisco Systems.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Many models of Macintosh favor the related RS-422 standard, mostly using circular mini-DIN connectors.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The Macintosh included a standard set of two ports for connection to a printer and a modem, but some PowerBook laptops had only one combined port to save space.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] 10P10C connectors can be found on some devices.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Another common connector is a 10 × 2 pin header common on motherboards and add-in cards which is usually converted via a ribbon cable to the more standard 9-pin DE-9 connector (and frequently mounted on a free slot plate or other part of the housing).
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Only one signal may be connected at the DCE end.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] When using a crossover cable to connect two DTE devices (null modem) this signal connects to DTR on the other device.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] When connecting two DTE devices (null modem) RI is not used and this signal should be connected to DTR on the other device in parallel with pin 2 (DCD), or, if that is not possible, left unconnected.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The *Request To Send* (RTS, V.24 circuit 105) signal pins are, in fact, nearly always used to carry the *Ready To Receive* (RTR, V.24 circuit 133) signal, but even when used for this purpose is still universally referred to as *RTS* in documentation.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] *Signal Ground* (G) is a common return for the other connections.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] *Signal Ground* (G) appears on two pins in some connectors but carry the same signal; the two pins should be connected in parallel at both ends (if possible) to provide a lower impedance connection.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] *Protective Ground* (PG), when available, is intended to be connected by each device to its own frame ground or similar for electrical safety.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Connecting Protective Ground to Signal Ground is a common practice but not recommended.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Operating systems usually create symbolic names for the serial ports of a computer, rather than requiring programs to refer to them by hardware address.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Unix-like operating systems usually label the serial port devices /dev/tty*.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] *TTY* is a common trademark-free abbreviation for *teletype*, a device commonly attached to early computers' serial ports, and * represents a string identifying the specific port; the syntax of that string depends on the operating system and the device.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] On Linux, serial ports intended for general communication have names that start with /dev/tty followed by a type prefix consisting of capital letters and ending with a sequence number starting with 0.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] For example, 8250/16550 UART serial ports are named /dev/ttyS* (/dev/ttyS0, /dev/ttyS1, ...etc); USB adapters appear as /dev/ttyUSB*, /dev/ttyACM*, or /dev/ttyHS*; other types have yet other prefixes.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Some virtual serial ports not intended for general communication have names that intentionally do not match this pattern.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The DOS and Windows environments refer to serial ports as COM ports and are named COM followed by a sequence number beginning with 1: COM1, COM2, ..etc.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] This list includes some of the more common devices that are connected to the serial port on a PC.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Some of these, such as modems and serial mice, are falling into disuse, while others are readily available.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Serial ports are very common on most types of microcontroller, where they can be used to communicate with a PC or other serial devices.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Since the control signals for a serial port can be driven by any digital signal, some applications used the control lines of a serial port to monitor external devices, without exchanging serial data.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] A common commercial application of this principle was for some models of uninterruptible power supply which used the control lines to signal loss of power, low battery, and other status information.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] At least some Morse code training software used a code key connected to the serial port to simulate actual code use; the status bits of the serial port could be sampled very rapidly and at predictable times, making it possible for the software to decipher Morse code.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Serial computer mice and low-power data converters (e.g.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] RS-232 to 422 converters) may draw their operating power from the received data or control signals..
[src:web-serial/serial-port] This mode is also known as "self powered".
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Serial standards provide for many different operating speeds as well as adjustments to the protocol to account for different operating conditions.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The most well-known options are speed, number of data bits per character, parity, and number of stop bits per character.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] In modern serial ports using a UART integrated circuit, all these settings can be software-controlled.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Hardware from the 1980s and earlier may require setting switches or jumpers on a circuit board.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The configuration for serial ports designed to be connected to a PC has become a de facto standard, usually stated as 9600/8-N-1.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Serial ports use two-level (binary) signaling, so the data rate in bits per second is equal to the symbol rate in baud.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The total speed includes bits for framing (stop bits, parity, etc.) and so the effective data rate is lower than the bit transmission rate.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] For example, with 8-N-1 character framing, only 80% of the bits are available for data; for every eight bits of data, two more framing bits are sent.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] A standard series of rates is based on multiples of the rates for electromechanical teleprinters; some serial ports allow many arbitrary rates to be selected, but the speeds on both sides of the connection must match for data to be received correctly.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Crystal oscillators with a frequency of 1.843200 MHz are sold specifically for this purpose.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] This is 16 times the fastest bit rate, and the serial port circuit can easily divide this down to lower frequencies as required.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The capability to set a bit rate does not imply that a working connection will result.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Not all bit rates are possible with all serial ports.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Some special-purpose protocols, such as MIDI for musical instrument control, use serial data rates other than the teleprinter standards.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Some serial port implementations can automatically choose a bit rate by observing what a connected device is sending and synchronizing to it.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The number of data bits in each character can be 5 (for Baudot code), 6 (rarely used), 7 (for true ASCII), 8 (for most kinds of data, as this size matches the size of a byte), or 9 (rarely used).
[src:web-serial/serial-port] 8 data bits are almost universally used in newer applications.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] 5 or 7 bits generally only make sense with older equipment, such as teleprinters.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Most serial communications designs send the data bits within each byte least significant bit first.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Also possible, but rarely used, is most significant bit first; this was used, for example, by the IBM 2741 printing terminal.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The order of bits is not usually configurable within the serial port interface but is defined by the host system.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] To communicate with systems that require a different bit ordering than the local default, local software can re-order the bits within each byte just before sending and just after receiving.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Aside from uncommon applications that use the last bit (usually the 9th) for some form of addressing or special signaling, mark or space parity is uncommon, as it adds no error detection information.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Odd parity is more useful than even parity since it ensures that at least one state transition occurs in each character, which makes it more reliable at detecting errors like those that could be caused by serial port speed mismatches.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The most common parity setting, however, is *none*, with error detection handled by a communication protocol.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] To allow detection of messages damaged by line noise, electromechanical teleprinters were arranged to print a special character when received data contained a parity error.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Stop bits sent at the end of every character allow the receiving signal hardware to detect the end of a character and to resynchronize with the character stream.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Electronic devices usually use one stop bit.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] If slow electromechanical teleprinters are used, one-and-one-half or two stop bits may be required.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The data/parity/stop (D/P/S) conventional notation specifies the framing of a serial connection.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The most common configuration for the personal computing devices is **8-N-1** (also spelled as 8N1, 8-None-1), in which there is one start bit, eight ("8") data bits, no ("N") parity bit, and one ("1") stop bit.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] In this notation, the parity bit is not included into the count of the data bits.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] For example, 7/E/1 (7E1) means that an even parity bit is added to the 7 data bits for a total of 8 bits between the start and stop bits.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The abbreviation is usually given together with the line speed in bits per second, as in "9600–8-N-1".
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The speed (or baud rate) includes bits for framing (stop bits, parity, etc.), thus the effective data rate is lower than the baud rate.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] For 8-N-1 encoding, only 80% of the bits are available for data (for every eight bits of data, ten bits are sent over the serial link — one start bit, the eight data bits, and the one stop bit).
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Flow control is used in circumstances where a transmitter might be able to send data faster than the receiver is able to process it.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] To cope with this, serial lines often incorporate a handshaking method.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] There are *hardware* and *software* handshaking methods.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The advantage of hardware handshaking is that it can be extremely fast, it works independently of imposed meaning, such as ASCII on the transferred data, and it is stateless.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] Its disadvantage is that it requires more hardware and cabling, and both ends of the connection must support the hardware handshaking protocol used.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The advantage of software handshaking is that it can be done with absent or incompatible hardware handshaking circuits and cabling.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The disadvantage, common to all in-band control signaling, is that it introduces complexities in ensuring that control messages get through even when data messages are blocked, and data can never be mistaken for control signals.
[src:web-serial/serial-port] The former is normally dealt with by the operating system or device driver; the latter normally by ensuring that control codes are escaped (such as in the Kermit protocol) or omitted by design (such as in ANSI terminal control).
[src:web-serial/serial-port] If **no handshaking** is employed, an overrun receiver might simply fail to receive data from the transmitter.
[src:web-serial/serialport-open] The **`open()`** method of the `SerialPort` interface returns a `Promise` that resolves when the port is opened.
[src:web-serial/serialport-open] A positive, non-zero value indicating the baud rate at which serial communication should be established.
[src:web-serial/serialport-open] An unsigned long integer indicating the size of the read and write buffers that are to be established.
[src:web-serial/serialport-open] An integer value of 7 or 8 indicating the number of data bits per frame.
[src:web-serial/serialport-open] The flow control type, either `"none"` or `"hardware"`.
[src:web-serial/serialport-open] An integer value of 1 or 2 indicating the number of stop bits at the end of the frame.
[src:web-serial/serialport-open] If `open()` is called when the port is already open.
[src:web-serial/web-serial-api] The **Web Serial API** provides a way for websites to read from and write to serial devices.
[src:web-serial/web-serial-api] These devices may be connected via a serial port, or be USB or Bluetooth devices that emulate a serial port.
[src:web-serial/web-serial-api] The Web Serial API provides the ability to connect to devices that communicate via a serial protocol.
[src:web-serial/web-serial-api] This includes USB and Bluetooth devices that connect over USB or Bluetooth but expose a virtual serial port to the operating system (via USB CDC-ACM or Bluetooth SPP).
[src:web-serial/web-serial-api] Note that these are distinct from devices accessed via the WebUSB API, — which provides raw access to USB devices that have not been claimed by an OS driver — or input devices that use the USB HID class, which are accessible via the WebHID API.
[src:web-serial/web-serial-api] Examples of serial devices include 3D printers, ESP32 devices, and microcontrollers such as the BBC micro:bit board.
[src:web-serial/web-serial-api] Provides attributes and methods for finding and connecting to serial ports from a web page.
[src:web-serial/web-serial-api] Provides access to a serial port on the host device.
[src:web-serial/web-serial-api] Returns a `Serial` object, which represents the main thread entry point into the Web Serial API.
[src:web-serial/web-serial-api] Returns a `Serial` object, which represents the worker entry point into the Web Serial API.
[src:web-serial/web-serial-api] Controls whether the current document is allowed to use the Web Serial API to communicate with serial devices, either directly connected via a serial port, or via USB or Bluetooth devices emulating a serial port.
[src:web-serial/web-serial-api] The following examples demonstrate some of the functionality provided by the Web Serial API.
[src:web-serial/web-serial-api] The following example shows how to check for available ports and allows the user to grant it permission to access additional ports.
[src:web-serial/web-serial-api] The `connect` and `disconnect` events let sites react when a device is connected or disconnected from the system.
[src:web-serial/web-serial-api] The `getPorts()` method is then called to see connected ports that the site already has access to.
[src:web-serial/web-serial-api] In this example, we use a `click` event handler on a button for this task.
[src:web-serial/web-serial-api] The outer loop handles non-fatal errors, creating a new reader until a fatal error is encountered and `SerialPort.readable` becomes `null`.
